==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|maydenhode|lang=enm}}, {{term|meidenhod|lang=enm}}, {{term|maȝdenhad|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|mæġdenhād||maidenhood}}, corresponding to {{suffix|maiden|hood}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈmeɪd(ə)nhʊd/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{context|uncountable|lang=en}} The condition of being a [[maiden]]; the time when one is a maiden or young girl.
#* '''1485''', Thomas Malory, ''Le Morte Darthur'', Book XI:
#*: I have gyven the the grettyst ryches and the fayryst floure that ever I had, and that is my '''maydynhode''' that I shall never have agayne – and therefore, jantyll knyght, owghe me youre good wyll.
# The state of an [[unwed]] female; [[virginity]].
# {{context|countable|lang=en}} The [[maidenhead]].
# [[freshness|Freshness]]; [[newness]].

